Neville, 1466, Leland, Coll. vi.; the order for the government of a nobleman's house, 1605, Archaeol. xiii. 315, and similar documents. At the coronation of Henry IV. the office of carver was claimed by the Earl of Somerset, half-brother to the King, in right of his earldom of Lincoln3 and on ordinary occasions the office was discharged by Bannerets, or Knights bachelors, who were called Knights of chamber, or, in their absence, by the Knights of household. See Liber Niger Edw. IV. Househ. Ord. 32. The Lords Henry Neville and Clinton were the chief carvers at the court of Henry VIII. 1526 ; and at all times the office seems to have been held by men of rank, and was conferred by patent.
